726204f.text:
Bowne Street (Ave.), south from Thirty-seventh Ave. (Washington Street), showing at the left foreground opnosite Thirty-seventh Ave., the old Bowne house later ovned by the Parsons family. This building was erected in 1661. In 1696 it was used as a meeting place for the Society of Friends. "It is the oldest identifiable place of worship in New York City." See clipping in Room 319, New ork Public Library, taken from "The Globe and Commercial Advertiser of New York" of Monday, September 26, 1921, and found in the Bowne papers. This house
still stands.
About 1909.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

726196f-a.text:
Bowne Street, at the S. E. corner of 37th Avenue, showing the John Bowne House,built in 1661. It was used as a meeting house by the Quakers and George Fox, founder of the sect, was entertained here. For additional data see "The Globe and Commercial
Advertiser," September 26, 1921, page 8.
About 1909
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

726197f-c.text:
Bowne Street, at the S. E. corner of 37th Avenue, showing the John Bowne House, built in 166l. This is the rear of the house. Officers of the Brttish Dragoons were quartered here during the Revolution. The direct descendents of Bowne occupied the house until 1878. For additional data see "The Globe and Commercial
Advertiser," September 26, 1921, p. 8.
Views 1,2: Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  1922
View 3: P. L. Sperr  August 24, 1935
